Chapter 2: Linear regression and model validation

This is a report that describes my work on the second weeks RStudio exercise in the course Introduction to Open Data Science. The dataset concerns the relationship between learning results and various factors related to learning styles in an introductory statistics class.

Part 1

I began by downloading the dataset from the file on my computer. I specified that commas were used as separators and that there was a header row in the file.
learning2014 <- read.table("/Users/ollisilvennoinen/IODS-project/chapter2.Rmd", sep = ",", header = TRUE)
I then explored the structure and dimensions of the file using the code below.
str(learning2014)
dim(learning2014)
Starting with the dimensions, the dataset is a 166x7 data frame, i.e.there are 166 observations and seven variables. Here is the output of the str function:
data.frame: 166 obs. of 7 variables:
$ age : int 53 55 49 53 49 38 50 37 37 42
$ attitude: num 3.7 3.1 2.5 3.5 3.7 3.8 3.5 2.9 3.8 2.1
$ points : int 25 12 24 10 22 21 21 31 24 26
$ gender : Factor w/ 2 levels F,M: 1 2 1 2 2 1 2 1 2 1
$ deep : num 3.75 2.88 3.88 3.5 3.75
$ surf : num 2.58 3.17 2.25 2.25 2.83
$ stra : num 3.38 2.75 3.62 3.12 3.62

As I stated above, the research question was what factors explain learning outcomes. Learning outcomes are measured by the variable points; this is the target variable. All the other variables are potential explanatory variables. Here are brief descriptions of the variables:
* age: age of the subjects
* attitude: attitude towards statistics, on a scale from 1 to 5
* points: points received on an exam
* gender: gender of the subjects (male or female)
* deep: mean score on questions related to deep learning
* surf: mean score on questions related to surface learning
* stra: mean score on questions related to strategic learning
More information on the dataset can be found on Kimmo Vehkalahtis webpage.

Part 2

After this preliminary look into the structure of the dataset, we may now move on to specifics. I explored the variables graphically using the function ggpairs:
install.packages("ggplot2")
library(ggplot2) install.packages("GGally") library(GGally) p <- ggpairs(learning2014, mapping = aes(col = gender), lower = list(combo = wrap("facethist", bins = 20))) p This yielded the following figure:

Men are indicated as turquoise, women as red. Based on the figure, genders do seem to pattern somewhat differently, though there do not appear to be any categorical distinctions, which is as expected. For the most part, the correlation coefficients, which can be seen on the upper-right side of the figure, are similar across genders. Exceptions include the interaction of deep and strategic learning as well as deep learning and attitude.
When we zoom in to points, which will be our variable of interest in what follows, the most notable correlation coefficients are those of attitude (0.437), surf (-0.144) and stra (0.146). When it comes to age, it is interesting to note that the two genders pattern differently.

Parts 3 and 4

Now that the structure of the dataset and the variables has been described, we can turn to the regression modelling. I decided to see the effects of the variables gender, attitude and stra. This allows me to explore both sociological and social-psychological factors in one model.
The following code was used to create the model:
model1 <- lm(points ~ gender + attitude + stra, data = learning2014)
The summary statistics of model1 were accessed using the summary function:
summary(model1)
Here is the output:
Call:
lm(formula = points ~ gender + attitude + stra, data = learning2014)

Residuals:
Min 1Q Median 3Q Max
-17.7179 -3.3285 0.5343 3.7412 10.9007

Coefficients:
Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)
(Intercept) 8.9798 2.4030 3.737 0.000258 ***
genderM -0.2236 0.9248 -0.242 0.809231
attitude 3.5100 0.5956 5.893 2.13e-08 ***
stra 0.8911 0.5441 1.638 0.103419

Signif. codes: 0 0.001 0.01 0.05 . 0.1 1

Residual standard error: 5.304 on 162 degrees of freedom
Multiple R-squared: 0.2051, Adjusted R-squared: 0.1904
F-statistic: 13.93 on 3 and 162 DF, p-value: 3.982e-08

The multiple R2 indicates that 20.5% of the exam score is explained by the model. Disappointingly, only attitude has a significant contribution to the value of points, meaning that the 20.5% is solely due to attitudinal factors. Therefore, I ran the regression again using only attitude as an explanatory variable.
model2 <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)
model2
The output is short and sweet:
Call: lm(formula = points ~ attitude, data = learning2014)

Coefficients: (Intercept) attitude
11.637 3.525

The result is, then, that a positive attitude correlates with exam success, while gender and a strategic learning style do not.

Part 5

To finalise the analysis, I produced diagnostic figures on the model. The code was as follows:
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(model2, which = c(1, 2, 5))
Here are the plots:

The first figure shows residuals versus fitted values. There is not much patterning here, which suggests that the assumptions of linear regression are not violated, at least not strongly. The second figure shows the QQ plot, in which the observations fall on the regression line, again suggesting that the assumptions are met reasonably well. The third plot measures residuals versus leverage. Since the leverage scores shown on the plot are small, no individual observations seem to have excessive leverage in comparison with the others, so the assumptions of linear regression modelling are met yet again.

Chapter 3: Logistic regression

This document is a report on RStudio exercise 3 on the IODS course. The goal is to study factors having an effect on alcohol consumption. The source of the dataset is the UCI Machine Learning Library; here is a link to where the dataset can be downloaded.

Getting started

Let us start by downloading the dataset from the data folder.

alc <- read.table("/Users/ollisilvennoinen/IODS-project/data/alc.csv", sep = ",", header = TRUE)

We then continue by looking at the columns in the data file:

colnames(alc)
##  [1] "X"          "school"     "sex"        "age"        "address"   
##  [6] "famsize"    "Pstatus"    "Medu"       "Fedu"       "Mjob"      
## [11] "Fjob"       "reason"     "nursery"    "internet"   "guardian"  
## [16] "traveltime" "studytime"  "failures"   "schoolsup"  "famsup"    
## [21] "paid"       "activities" "higher"     "romantic"   "famrel"    
## [26] "freetime"   "goout"      "Dalc"       "Walc"       "health"    
## [31] "absences"   "G1"         "G2"         "G3"         "alc_use"   
## [36] "high_use"

The dataset contains a number of background variables as well as the variable that we are interested in studying, i.e., high_use, whether a given participant has high alcohol use or not. The page that contains the data files (linked above) also provides information on the variables. There are 35 variables and 382 observations (in addition, there is a column that gives a unique identifying integer for each observation).

In this assignment, I shall examine the effects of the following variables on high alcohol use:
* sex: my hypothesis is that males use alcohol more than females
* age (ranging from 15 to 22): my hypothesis is that the older the student, the more likely they are to display high use of alcohol
* Medu (ranging from 0 to 4 on an ordinal scale, 0 being low and 4 high education): my hypothesis is that when a childs mother has low educational attainment, the child is more likely to use alcohol; this is based on the assumption that the mothers educational attainment is a reliable indicator of the social status of the family (so I do not assume a causal relationship from the mothers education to their childs alcohol use)
* G3 (average of final period grade in math and Portuguese, ranging from 0 to 20): my hypothesis is that the lower the grade, the higher the likelihood of high alcohol use

Initial explorations of the variables

Let us begin by considering each variable in isolation, starting with sex. Here is the breakdown of high users of alcohol by gender (note that TRUE means that the informant is a high user of alcohol). As the cross-tabulation shows, men seem to be more likely to be high users.

table(alc$high_use, alc$sex)
##        
##           F   M
##   FALSE 156 112
##   TRUE   42  72

Next up is the age of the informants, which I visualise using a boxplot; for this, I need the ggplot2 package.

library(ggplot2)
g1 <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = high_use, y = age))
g1 + geom_boxplot() + ylab("age")

As the boxplot shows, those who are coded as being high users are older on average, as my original hypothesis predicted.

Third, I look at Medu, this time using a mosaic plot.

plot(table(alc$high_use, alc$Medu))

The verdict for my hypothesis is mixed: getting 1 is more common for the high user group, but so is getting 3.

Finally, I shall have a look at final grades and high alcohol use.

g2 <- ggplot(alc, aes(x = G3, col = high_use))
g2 + geom_dotplot()
## `stat_bindot()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

It seems that FALSE is more common towards the upper end of the grade scale while the TRUEs are concentrated towards the middle. This would support my hypothesis.

Logistic regression

I now fit a logistic regression model on the dataset, using the glm function.

m <- glm(high_use ~ sex + age + Medu + G3, data = alc, family = "binomial")
summary(m)
## 
## Call:
## glm(formula = high_use ~ sex + age + Medu + G3, family = "binomial", 
##     data = alc)
## 
## Deviance Residuals: 
##     Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max

## Medu         0.06228    0.11103   0.561 0.574830

## Residual deviance: 440.90  on 377  degrees of freedom
## AIC: 450.9
## 
## Number of Fisher Scoring iterations: 4

Of the four variables that I chose, only two are significant: sex and final grade. Since sex is a factor variable, females have been chosen by R as the reference level and the model summary only shows the effect that maleness has on alcohol consumption. It turns out that the effect is positive, i.e.that being a male means that one is more likely to use alcohol. The other significant predictor is exam grade, which turns out to have a negative effect, though the effect seems to be slight. Still, this does not conform with my original hypothesis.

I now compute the confidence intervals.

library(dplyr)
## 
## Attaching package: 'dplyr'
## The following objects are masked from 'package:stats':
## 
##     filter, lag
## The following objects are masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     intersect, setdiff, setequal, union
OR <- coef(m) %>% exp
CI <- confint(m) %>% exp
## Waiting for profiling to be done...
cbind(OR, CI)
##                     OR        2.5 %    97.5 %
## (Intercept) 0.02494492 0.0006625863 0.8709274
## sexM        2.40684013 1.5257844762 3.8361931
## age         1.20383314 0.9907875565 1.4680981
## Medu        1.06426277 0.8572699654 1.3260686
## G3          0.92460997 0.8605396713 0.9919652

The confidence intervals confirm the analysis presented above: the intervals for age and the mothers education include 1.00, which means that they are unreliable predictors. The intervals for sex and grade are on either side of 1.00, which means that they work as predictors.

Predictions

Lastly, I check how well the model manages to predict the observations.

probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = alc$probability > 0.5)
table(high_use = alc$high_use, prediction = alc$probability > 0.5)
##         prediction
## high_use FALSE TRUE
##    FALSE   258   10
##    TRUE    103   11

The value FALSE is predicted with a high accuracy. By contrast, TRUE is quite weakly predicted. Therefore, the model requires a bit more work.

Now I turn crime rate or crim into a categorical variable by first binning the observations and then using the bins as categorical classes. There will be four bins based on the quantiles of the variable.

bins <- quantile(c(boston_scaled$crim))
crime <- cut(boston_scaled$crim, breaks = bins, include.lowest = TRUE, label = c("low", "med_low", "med_high", "high"))
table(crime)

The LDA is then plotted using a biplot.

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "red", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

Clustering

Lastly, I shall apply k-means clustering to the Boston dataset. I first need to download the original dataset and scale it again.

data("Boston")
boston_scaled <- scale(Boston)

I shall make the clustering analysis using Euclidean distances. First, I calculate these, and then I perform the k-means clustering itself. Finally, I plot the clusters.

dist_eu <- dist(boston_scaled)
km <-kmeans(dist_eu, centers = 10)
pairs(boston_scaled, col = km$cluster)

However, this is only a first stab on the clusters since I have not yet determined the correct number of clusters in the data. To do this, I need to calculate the total within cluster sum of squares (WCSS) and inspect the result visually to see where the plot elbows.

k_max <- 10
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(dist_eu, k)$tot.withinss})
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

The plot shows that the elbow is around 2, so this is the number of clusters I need to go for. Thus, I run the k-means analysis again, this time setting the number of centers at 2.

km <-kmeans(dist_eu, centers = 10)
pairs(boston_scaled, col = km$cluster)

human <- read.csv("http://s3.amazonaws.com/assets.datacamp.com/production/course_2218/datasets/human2.txt", header = TRUE)

The human dataset contains various indicators of the well-being of various countries. As the summary shows, there are altogether 155 observations (i.e.countries). The variables are the following:
* Edu2.FM: the ratio of females to males in secondary education
* Labo.FM: the ratio of females to males in the labour force
* Edu.Exp: expected number of years spent in schooling
* Life.Exp: life expectancy in years
* GNI: gross national income
* Mat.Mor: the relativised number of mothers who die at childbirth
* Ado.Birth: the rate of teenage pregnancies leading to childbirth
* Parli.F: the percentage of female parliamentarians

Overview of the variables

We may now have a look at the variables in more detail. First, we have a look at their distributions.

library(GGally)
## 
## Attaching package: 'GGally'
## The following object is masked from 'package:dplyr':
## 
##     nasa
ggpairs(human)

The above plot shows that the variables display varying degrees of skewness. For instance, maternal mortality is highly skewed so that the mean value is close to zero. By contrast, the expected number of years spent in schooling appears to be almost normally distributed.
We may then see if the variables are correlated by creating a correlation matrix.

library(dplyr)
library(corrplot)
cor(human) %>% corrplot

There are strong positive correlations between adolescent birth rate and maternal mortality on the one hand, and life expectancy and expected years spent in schooling on the other. The strongest negative correlation is between maternal mortality and life expectancy. Other strongly negative correlations obtain between maternal mortality and ratio of females to males in secondary education; maternal mortality and expected years spent in schooling; adolescent birthrate and expected years spent in schooling; as well as adolescent birthrate and life expectancy. By contrast, the ration of females to males in the labour market and the proportion of female parliamentarians are only weakly if at all correlated with the other variables.

PCA on non-standardised data

Now we perform our first attempt at a Principal Component Analysis (PCA) of the dataset. Note that we have not standardised the numeric predictors at this stage, and as we saw above, the variables are quite divergent in their distributional properties. We also visualise the analysis by means of a biplot.

pca_human <- prcomp(human)

The result is a much clearer picture, with some variables associated clearly with PC1 and others with PC2.

Interpreting the PCA

The variables form three broad groups in the second PCA analysis.
* The first group consists of variables Edu.Exp, Edu2.FM, Life.Exp and GNI. They are all very closely aligned with negative values of PC1. A high score in these variables is associated with western countries. They display equality, well-being and prosperity.
* The second group consists of variables Mat.Mor and Ado.Birth. They are also associated with PC1, but correlate positively with it and are thus diametrically opposite to the first group. They display a lack of basic healthcare.
* The third group consists of variables Labo.FM and Parli.F. They are associated with PC2. Recall that these variables had little correlation with the others. They are related to formal gender equality, which, interestingly, may be fulfilled in both rich and poor countries.
